-- China Southern, ICBC, Goldwind, Zijin: China Equity Preview
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2010-10-08T00:24:42Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-07/china-southern-airlines-icbc-goldwind-zijin-mining-china-stock-preview.html
The following companies may have  unusual 
price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses,
and share prices are as of the close of Sept. 30.  The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of China’s
stock exchanges, gained 44.98, or 1.7 percent, to 2,655.66 on Sept.
30. The  CSI 300 Index  rose 2.1 percent to 2,945.57. China’s markets
were closed from Oct. 1 until yesterday for the National Day holiday.  Developers: The Shanghai municipal government plans to rein in
the property market by restricting new home purchases to one per
household, the city government said on its website Oct. 7. Other
measures include boosting land supply, introducing differentiated
credit policies and tax changes, the statement said.  The central government will levy a tax on some property as a trial
in select cities before expanding the measures nationwide, the
Securities News reported today, citing a Chinese taxation official
it did not identify.  China Vanke Co.  (000002 CH), the nation’s largest publicly traded
developer, gained 7.6 percent to 8.40 yuan.  Poly Real Estate Group
Co.  (600048 CH), the second-biggest developer, advanced 8.9 percent
to 12.36 yuan.  China Southern Airlines Co.  (600029 CH): The carrier said its
board approved unit Xiamen Airlines’ purchase of 10 Boeing aircraft.
The shares added 1.2 percent to 8.28 yuan.  Huadian Energy Co.  (600726 CH): The company said it will buy shares
in three Heilongjiang-based power companies from parent China Huadian
Corp. The shares added 1.1 percent to 3.57 yuan.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (601398 CH): The
world’s largest lender by market value said it received approval from
the China Banking Regulatory Commission for a rights offer of A and
H shares. The stock added 0.8 percent to 4.04 yuan.  Xinjiang Goldwind Science & Technology Co.  (002202 CH): China’s
second-biggest maker of wind turbines said its Hong Kong-listed shares
will having their trading debut today. Goldwind sold 395.3 million
shares at HK$17.98 each, the top end of the price range. The shares
added 1.6 percent to 19.26 yuan in Shenzhen.  Zijin Mining Group Co . (601899 CH): China’s largest gold producer
said it was fined a less-than-expected 9.6 million yuan ($1.4 million)
for a July acid-waste spill. The shares added 8.8 percent to 7.27
yuan.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Linus Chua at   lchua@bloomberg.net  